Per the Governor's Executive Order 20-81, all K-12 students and staff will be required to wear a cloth face mask or face covering in schools and on buses this year, unless they have a disability, medical or mental health condition.

As the school year approaches, we recommend that students try out different types of face masks to find one that fits well and is comfortable enough for long-term wear. We encourage parents and guardians to practice wearing masks with your student(s) at home to get them comfortable before the first day of school.

The CDC has a great list of do’s and don’ts for selecting, wearing and cleaning masks:
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/about-face-coverings.html

The annual Westonka Public Schools back-to-school booklet is going digital this year. The Fall 2020 Roadmap linked below and posted on the district website contains important information about the 2020-21 school year, including:

-Superintendent’s message
-Back-to-school dates
-Health & safety protocols
-Westonka’s Safe Learning Plan overview
-District calendar
-Curriculum updates
-Nondiscrimination and bullying policies
-Free and reduced price meal application

Hard copies of the booklet will be available in school and district offices prior to the start of school. Copies will also be mailed to families that have indicated unreliable home Internet access.

We look forward to welcoming Westonka Public Schools students and staff back to school on Tuesday, September 8!

On Monday night, the Westonka School Board adopted by unanimous vote Westonka Public Schools’ Safe Learning Plan for the 2020-21 school year. Based on current health data, Westonka plans to begin the year with early learning through grade 4 in the In-Person Learning Model and grades 5-12 in the Hybrid Learning Model. Please read the Borg Report and visit our Safe Learning Plan web pages for more details.

Important deadlines: We are asking that ALL families let us know transportation plans for their student(s) in Skyward Family Access by Monday, Aug. 17. Similarly, families choosing 100% distance learning through Westonka Public Schools must opt in by Aug. 17 in Family Access. Families will be asked to commit to the Distance Only model for the entire first quarter of the 2020-21 school year (Sept. 8-Nov. 6).

Board Approves Westonka's Safe Learning Plan

Based on current health data, Westonka plans to begin the year with early learning through grade 4 in the In-Person Learning Model and grades 5-12 in the Hybrid Learning Model. Please read the Borg Report and visit our Safe Learning Plan web pages for more details.

Important deadlines: We are asking that ALL families let us know transportation plans for their student(s) in Skyward Family Access by Monday, Aug. 17. Similarly, families choosing 100% distance learning through Westonka Public Schools must opt in by Aug. 17 in Family Access. Families will be asked to commit to the Distance Only model for the entire first quarter of the 2020-21 school year (Sept. 8-Nov. 6).

post_text:
Following a consultation Aug. 3 with state and county public health officials, Westonka Public Schools is recommending an in-person learning model for grades K-4 and a hybrid learning model for grades 5-12 to start the 2020-21 school year.

On Monday, Aug. 10, the district will present the Westonka School Board with its start-of-year proposal, as well as detailed plans for all three educational models outlined by the state (in-person, distance and hybrid learning). These plans have been carefully crafted (and re-crafted) over the past several months with input from Westonka administrators, teachers, support staff and families. Topics will include instruction, health and safety procedures, food service delivery, cleaning schedules, transportation, childcare and more.

The Aug. 10 school board meeting will be held at 7 p.m. at the Westonka Performing Arts Center. The meeting will also be streamed live to the district’s YouTube channel:
www.youtube.com/WestonkaEdge

Learn more about Westonka's start-of-year proposal on the district website: https://bit.ly/BorgReport8420

We're anticipating that the district will need a larger pool of substitute teachers in order to operate school this fall. Westonka Schools is asking all community members to consider supporting their local schools by becoming a short call sub for the district. If you or someone you know is interested in being a short call substitute teacher, the time to start the application process is now!

Short Call Substitute Teacher Rate of Pay: $175.00/day during the COVID-19 pandemic

Westonka will reimburse the PELSB licensure fee ($91.95) once you have subbed for five full days in a Westonka assignment.

Eligible families can complete an online application before June 30 at https://mn.p-ebt.org/en/

Westonka Public Schools is always here to support our students and families, especially during times of heartbreak, anger and confusion. Even during the summer months, if your student is struggling with the death of George Floyd or other trauma, please reach out to your school principal and we will provide resources and support for your family.

Principal contact information: https://www.westonka.k12.mn.us/Page/829

The Minnesota Department of Education has also shared helpful resources for talking with children about traumatic events and tragedies: https://education.mn.gov/MDE/dse/safe/bprev/MDE071470

Today, Governor Tim Walz announced that Minnesota schools will remain closed and will continue with distance learning for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. This decision was made to slow the spread of COVID-19 and reduce its impact on our healthcare system and vulnerable populations. This is not the news that we were hoping for, but we fully support the state’s decision to prioritize the health and safety of our community.

Please read the Borg Report for more information about the school closure extension and what it means for you and your student.

post_text: Please read an announcement about Summer Adventure Club registration, which opens Wednesday, April 1.
shared_text:
Westonka Community Education and Services
March 26 at 3:07 PM ·

We have made the decision to still move forward with our Summer 2020 Adventure Club registration on April 1 as planned. While there are a lot of unknowns, we feel it is important that we move forward with our planning so that in the event that we can hold Summer Adventure Club we are prepared. During registration you will be asked to enter a credit card to complete the registration process. We want to be empathetic towards the fact that families may be working through difficult financial situations during this time, so we have modified our registration fee process so that your card will NOT be charged the $40 registration fee unless we are able to run summer programming. This also means that if we cannot run our summer program, or if your plans change, registrations would be canceled free of charge as long as your cancelation comes prior to the first day of summer programming. If the program is able to run, the credit card you entered would be charged on the first day of summer programming, June 8.

post_text:
All Westonka Schools families are eligible to have meals delivered to school bus stops free of charge beginning Wednesday, March 18.

All meals will be delivered between the hours of 11 a.m. and 1 p.m. We request orders to be submitted by 8 p.m. in order for meals to be delivered the following day. Meals may also be ordered via telephone by calling (952) 491-8088; please leave a voicemail.

Breakfast will be delivered with each lunch meal for the following day. A breakfast will include at least a grain, a fruit and milk. Lunches will include a grain, a protein, a fruit or vegetable and a milk.

Note: The buses or vans used for delivery will say Westonka Bus Service or Westonka Public Schools on the side. Additional bags of food will be available at each stop in the event that orders are not submitted the evening before.

The delivery service will not be available over Westonka’s Spring Break, March 23-27. We plan to continue food delivery service should the school closure be extended beyond March 27. Watch for more details.

NO SCHOOL FOR STUDENTS MARCH 16-27

On Sunday morning, March 15, Governor Tim Walz announced that all public and private schools in Minnesota will be shut down beginning this Wednesday, March 18, through at least March 27 in light of the COVID-19 situation.

Westonka Public Schools has made the decision to cancel school for students starting Monday, March 16, to allow for in-district collaborative planning amongst staff prior to Westonka’s spring break. All district staff will report to their buildings on Monday, March 16, and Tuesday, March 17.

Please read the full announcement for additional details.

Westonka primary school students celebrated the 100th day of kindergarten in style last month.

At Shirley Hills Primary School, students dressed like 100-year-old grandmas and grandpas to mark the occasion and did several activities featuring the number 100. Hilltop Primary School students celebrated by bringing in 100 items from home, making 100th day trail mix by counting out each piece, doing 100 exercises, and more!

If a person wants to be treated with kindness, they have to throw the "kindness boomerang," and kindness can come back to them.

Through music, games and small and large group discussions, and with the help of some Mound Westonka High School mentors, Shirley Hills Primary School and Hilltop Primary School fourth-graders learned that valuable lesson earlier this month at the Youth Frontiers Kindness Retreat®.

post_text: On Tuesday, Nov. 5, Westonka School District residents approved a new 10-year operating levy in support of our students. Unofficial election results are as follows: 65.24% Yes (1,498 votes), 34.76% No (798 votes). Thank you to everyone who voted! #ProgressingTogether
text: On Tuesday, Nov. 5, Westonka School District residents approved a new 10-year operating levy in support of our students. Unofficial election results are as follows: 65.24% Yes (1,498 votes), 34.76% No (798 votes). Thank you to everyone who voted! #ProgressingTogether

post_text:
Today, Tuesday, Nov. 5, is Election Day.

Polls will be open from 7:00 a.m. to 8:00 p.m. Find where you will vote using the Minnesota Secretary of State pollfinder: https://pollfinder.sos.state.mn.us/

Westonka School District residents will be asked to vote on a single ballot question to revoke all three of the district’s current operating levies and replace them with a single, 10-year levy with a tiered payment structure. Voters will also elect four school board members to four-year terms.

Please visit the referendum page on the district website to learn more about the levy referendum and school board election: www.westonka.k12.mn.us/referendum.

#ProgressingTogether

In-person absentee/early voting for the Nov. 5, 2019, school district election is conducted at the Westonka Educational Service Center, 5901 Sunnyfield Road E, Minnetrista (across the parking lot from Mound Westonka High School), during regular business hours, 8:00 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.

During the last week of absentee voting, Oct. 29 through Nov. 4, in-person absentee voters will be able to vote by “direct ballot,” meaning they will be able to feed their ballot into a ballot counter just as is done on Election Day. Due to public response to direct ballot absentee voting in recent elections, the district will offer some extended early voting hours that week. Early voting will be open the following times during the direct balloting period:

Tuesday, Oct. 29 - 8:00 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.
Wednesday, Oct. 30 - 8:00 a.m. to 7:00 p.m.
Thursday, Oct. 31 - 8:00 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.
Friday, Nov. 1 - 8:00 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.
Saturday, Nov. 2 - 10:00 a.m. to 12:30 p.m.
Monday, Nov. 4 - 7:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m.

To find where you will vote on Election Day, Tuesday, Nov. 5, please visit www.mnvotes.org.

School board candidate profiles, tax charts, voting information and more can be found at www.westonka.k12.mn.us/referendum.
shared_text:
Westonka Public Schools
September 20, 2019 at 4:23 PM ·

On Nov. 5, 2019, Westonka residents will be asked to vote on a "revoke and replace" levy with a tiered payment structure. The district currently has three voter-approved operating levies in place, totaling $1,096 per pupil. These would be replaced with a single, 10-year levy with a two-step increase.

Prepared and paid for by Westonka Public Schools. This video is for informational purposes only and is not meant to advocate for or against a ballot question.

Early voting for the Nov. 5, 2019 election is now open at the Westonka Educational Service Center, 5901 Sunnyfield Road E, Minnetrista, weekdays during regular business hours, 8 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Save time by doing the following before you come in to vote:

1. Familiarize yourself with the school district referendum and school board candidates by visiting www.westonka.k12.mn.us/referendum

2. Visit the Minnesota Secretary of State website, mnvotes.org, to:
• Check your voter registration (Eligible persons can register online through Oct. 15 or at the polls)
• View a sample ballot

3. Download and fill out an Absentee Ballot Application: https://www.westonka.k12.mn.us/cms/lib/MN01809628/Centricity/Domain/289/2019-reg-absentee-ballot-app-1pg.pdf (Paper copies are also available at the ESC). If you are already a registered voter, this application is all you will need to vote early in person.

On Nov. 5, 2019, Westonka residents will be asked to vote on a "revoke and replace" levy with a tiered payment structure. The district currently has three voter-approved operating levies in place, totaling $1,096 per pupil. These would be replaced with a single, 10-year levy with a two-step increase.

Prepared and paid for by Westonka Public Schools. This video is for informational purposes only and is not meant to advocate for or against a ballot question.
